docs.abstract: Kamala Harris and Joe Biden will face off again on the debate stage later this month, and Bernie Sanders and Elizabeth Warren will headline the other half of the two-night event.

headline.main: Here Are the Lineups for the Next Democratic Debates

docs.abstract: Ms. Williamson, a spiritual adviser and long shot presidential candidate, stood by her claim that antidepressants are overprescribed, which experts say stigmatizes mental illness.
docs.snippet: Ms. Williamson, a spiritual adviser and long shot presidential candidate, stood by her claim that antidepressants are overprescribed, which experts say stigmatizes mental illness.
docs.lead_paragraph: When the self-help author Marianne Williamson appeared on the presidential debate stage last month, Twitter users delighted in unearthing her old comments about vibrations and “morphic” fields. But her performance also put a spotlight on much more serious comments about mental health.

headline.main: ‘I Should Be More Careful With Twitter’: Marianne Williamson on Those Mental Health Comments
headline.print_headline: Mental Health, Drugs and a Candidate’s Tweets

docs.abstract: Impeachment is popular among Democratic voters, but remains secondary to issues like health care. And their support is tempered by the worry that nothing will come of it.
docs.snippet: Impeachment is popular among Democratic voters, but remains secondary to issues like health care. And their support is tempered by the worry that nothing will come of it.
docs.lead_paragraph: BOW, N.H. — As Senator Elizabeth Warren neared the conclusion of her remarks on Saturday to a few hundred activists at a house party in this small town just south of the state capital, she made a solemn vow to “protect our democracy.”

headline.main: Why Aren’t 2020 Democrats Talking About Impeachment? Because Voters Aren’t Asking
headline.print_headline: Why Impeachment Talk Is Rare on Campaign Trail

docs.abstract: Moderate underdogs kicked off the Detroit debates by targeting the top candidates with charges of “wish-list economics” and “impossible promises” on health care.
docs.snippet: Moderate underdogs kicked off the Detroit debates by targeting the top candidates with charges of “wish-list economics” and “impossible promises” on health care.
docs.lead_paragraph: DETROIT — The leading liberals in the Democratic presidential primary, Senators Bernie Sanders and Elizabeth Warren, strenuously fought back on Tuesday against accusations of making fanciful promises and imperiling the party’s prospects against President Trump, as a group of moderate underdogs sought to slow their momentum in the second round of debates.

headline.main: Sanders and Warren Battle Accusations of ‘Fairy Tale’ Promises as Intraparty Rift Flares
headline.print_headline: Leading Liberals  Fend Off Attacks  On Big Promises

docs.abstract: Mr. Booker, a senator from New Jersey, has made numerous proposals to overhaul the justice system, including one that was signed into law.
docs.snippet: Mr. Booker, a senator from New Jersey, has made numerous proposals to overhaul the justice system, including one that was signed into law.
docs.lead_paragraph: Perhaps no issue is more central to the career of Senator Cory Booker of New Jersey than criminal justice reform. His bipartisan criminal justice bill, the First Step Act, was signed into law in December, and Mr. Booker has made numerous other proposals to overhaul the justice system.

headline.main: Cory Booker on Criminal Justice Reform

docs.abstract: The governor of Washington has made climate change his campaign’s singular focus, going so far as to call for a climate debate.

docs.lead_paragraph: Gov. Jay Inslee of Washington is running a campaign almost singularly focused on combating climate change. It is his signature issue.

docs.abstract: Mr. Castro, a former housing secretary and San Antonio mayor, was the first Democratic candidate in the 2020 campaign to release an immigration plan.

docs.lead_paragraph: Julián Castro, a former housing secretary under President Barack Obama, was the first candidate to release an immigration plan. It’s one of the centerpieces of what he refers to as his “People First” platform.

docs.abstract: Mr. Bennet, a senator from Colorado, may be best known for helping negotiate a comprehensive immigration proposal in 2013.

docs.lead_paragraph: Senator Michael Bennet of Colorado may be best known for being part of the so-called Gang of Eight: four Democratic and four Republican senators who negotiated a comprehensive immigration proposal in 2013.

headline.main: Michael Bennet and the Immigration Compromise That Failed
